03973nam a22006255i 9780823296729DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221982nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232967297 a10.1515/97808232967292doi  a(DE-B1597)575289  a(OCoLC)1322124226  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0220002bisacsh1 aO'Connell, Robert J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTeilhard's Vision of the Past :bThe Making of a Method /cRobert J. O'Connell. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©1982  a1 online resource (205 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAbbreviations -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 "Seeing": Teilhard and the "New Positivism" -- t2 Seeing With an Educated Eye -- t3 Seeing "Wholes" -- t4 Science as History and Product of History -- t5 Science, "Hypothesis," and the Reality of Evolution -- t6 Entropy vs. Evolution -- t7 Toward a New Science of the Past -- t8 Crisis and Faith: In Evolution -- t9 The Phenomenon of Man: A Scientific Memoire -- t10 Toward Evaluating Teilhard's Vision of the Past: The Appropriate Questions -- tAfterword -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Phenomenon of Man, by Pierre Teilhard de Chardin, has been characterized as metaphysics, poetry, and mysticism-virtually everything except what its author claimed it was: a "purely scientific mémoir." Professor O'Connell here follows up on a nest of clues, uncovered first in an early unpublished essay, then in the series of essays contained principally in The Vision of the Past. Those clues all point to Teilhard's intimate familiarity with the philosophy of science propounded by the celebrated Pierre Duhem. It was Duhem's central claim that science, to remain true to itself, must aim at establishing a genuine "natural classification" phenomenal reality. That insight, Professor O'Connell argues, guided Teilhard's lifelong effort to describe the "imposed reality-factors" which science in its variety of forms suggests as ingredients and operative at every phase in the evolutionary development of planet Earth. Limiting his focus to the way Teilhard unfolded his vision of the past, Professor O'Connell concludes that those who deprecate Teilhard as unscientific betray little awareness of how sophisticated his understanding of science truly was.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831107432960 cprintz978082321090940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329672940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823296729423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823296729/original  a978-3-11-074329-6  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK